EXECUTIVE SUMMARY-
This document is an end-to-end walkthrough of the AI Scalability Platform application starting from the Home page: it explains how the React frontend initializes and issues API calls, how the Node/Express backend server.js and controllers) handles those requests and interacts with Snowflake, and how responses propagate back to update the UI. It highlights key routes (pipelines, analytics, templates, SPCS), helper utilities, relevant DB tables, and step-by-step tracing guidance for mapping UI actions to SQL queries.
1.	Open the Application:
 

2.	Login Page:
•	This is the login page of the application. User will have to enter their credentials to continue to the application.
•	Data Entry:
	Username: Enter your snowflake username
	Password: Enter the correct snowflake password.
•	Click on “Sign in” button

•	















3.	Home Page
•	This is the Home Page of the AI Scalability Platform which contains four option cards: “Talk to Document”, “Talk to Data”, “regulatory Audit Compliance” and “Lineage Graph”. It also shows the type of user privileges for the account at the right hand-side in the top bar.
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app
•	API Calls:
	chatbots: This API gives response for existing chatbots list.
	pipeline: This API gives response for the existing pipelines.
	current-user: This API fetches the current user of the application.
	Prompts: This API gives response for the existing prompts.
	current-role: This role represents the administrative privileges.
	current-access: The current user’s effective permissions now of the request.
•	Click on “account” icon at the right top of the page














4.	Options accounts:
•	The user gets three options for accounts: “About”, “Settings” and “Access Control”.
-	About: Gives the usage of the icon
•	Click on “Settings”

















 
5.	Settings page:
•	We can change the configuration through the settings, such as updating the user email ID to receive error notifications. 
•	Data Entry:
-	Write a valid email address where the user wants the error notifications. Then click on save and send verification.
•	 API Call:
-	Update_procedure_email: This post API updates the mail and the notification for errors will be sent on this mail.

•	Click on “Access Control”















6.	Access Control Page
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/access-control
•	This page manages all the accesses according to the roles of the user. Admin can change the privileges assigned to different users by modifying the access through checking the checkboxes and then click on “Save Permissions”. The new access will get updated.
•	API Calls:
-	current-access: Checks the current access of the user, if he has permissions to change the access.
-	update: After clicking on save permission this API updates all the permissions according to the new changes made by the administrator.


7.	Talk to Document: 
•	Click on “Talk to document”
8.	Application Page
•	This is the Application page for the talk to document flow. Here, we have three options: “Data Preparation”, “Experiment and Deploy”, “Deployed Application”.
-	Data Preparation: Contains all the pipelines and the options to select new pipelines.
-	Experiment and Deploy: Contains the existing chatbots and user can also create new chatbot.
-	Deployed Application: Contains the deployed chatbot from which user can ask answers as per user requirement.
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/application




	Click on “Data Preparation”
















9.	Data Preparation page for talk to Document
•	Contains existing pipeline and the user can create a new pipeline according to the requirements.
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/data-preparation
•	API calls:
-	pipelines: This API gives response for existing pipelines.
•	Click on “Create new Pipeline”



















10.	Create Pipeline page for Talk to Document
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/create-pipeline
•	Data Entry:
-	Give a new pipeline name (name should be unique than existing pipeline).
-	Select the preferred data storage type.

 

11.	Create Pipeline page for Talk to Document (CLOUD STORAGE)

•	Data Entry:
-	Select the database.
-	Select the schema present inside the selected database.
-	Choose a file location.
-	Select the pdf files inside the selected file location (Optional).
-	Then, select the chunking method.
-	Select the chunking size.
-	Select the chunking overlap.
•	API call:
-	databases: This API gives response to the existing databases.
-	schemas: This API gives response for the schema present in the selected database.
-	stages:
-	stage-files: Gives response for the files inside the stage.



















12.	Create Pipeline page for Talk to Document (Database storage)

•	Data Entry:
-	Select the database.
-	Select the schema present inside the selected database.
-	Select the tables present inside the schema accordingly (Multiple tables can be selected).
-	Select the column inside the table.
-	Select the attribute (Optional).
•	API calls:
-	databases: This API gives response to the existing databases.
-	schemas: This API gives response for the schema present in the selected database.
-	tables: This API gives response for the tables inside the schema.
-	Columns: This API gives names of the columns of the selected table. 
•	Click on “NEXT”

13.	Review Pipeline page (Cloud Storage)
o	Here, The user can review the pipeline configuration before creating the pipeline.
o	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/review-pipeline
•	API calls:
-	run-chunking: This POST API chunks the available pdf data and saves it in table format (After clicking on “Submit”).
-	Submit-pipeline: API saves the pipeline in backend (After clicking on “Submit”).


14.	Review Pipeline page (Database)
•	API calls:
-	Create-search-service:
-	Submit-pipeline: API saves the pipeline in backend (After clicking on “Submit”).

15.	Pipeline successfully submitted page
•	If the pipeline successfully gets submitted, then user will get this “Pipeline Submitted” response. Else, the page will throw an error message.

	Click on “Application” from the menu bar














16.	Application Page of Talk to document







	Click on “Experiment and Deploy” card

17.	Experimentation and Deploy page
•	Contains all the existing chatbots in which the user can do configurations as well as ask questions through prompts and the user also gets the option to create a new Chatbot.
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/search-chatbot

	Click on “Create new Chatbot” button
















18.	Create new chatbot page
•	In this page the user must fill all the necessary information and give a unique name to chatbot then only the chatbot can be created successfully.
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/experimentation
•	Data Entry:
-	Give a unique name to your chatbot by clicking on the edit option in the middle of the page
-	Select pipeline in the right panel.
-	Select the prompts you want to use.
-	Select the models you want to have in your chatbot (Max 3 models).

	Click on “Create chatbot” button

















•	If the API successfully responds then the user will get the success message, else it will throw an error message.
•	API calls:
-	create: create API posts the chatbot configuration to the back end.
-	chatbots: It calls the data of the chatbot created from the backend.
•	After creating the chatbot the user can directly give a prompt as per his needs

19.	Response of the chatbot
•	This page shows the response generated by the models here we have the option to select between the three models which we chose for the chatbot. 
•	API Calls:
-	agent: This API gives the prompts to the selected models.
-	chatbot-response: Generates response according to prompt.


	Click on the “Model Comparison” option:

20.	Model Comparison page
•	The model comparison option shows you the responsiveness and correctness of the models you chose as per their responses. It displays the “Total Conversation”, “Success Rate (%)”, “Recommended Model”, “Metric vs Score per Model” and “CSAT by model”.
•	 API Calls:
-	avg-metrics: Gives the metrics vs score per model
-	csat-scores: Generates the CSAT Score graph.
-	Total-conversation: Gives the number of total conversations with chatbot.
-	Success-rate: Calculates the success-rate of the models.
	Click on “Deploy” button:

21.	Deploy chatbot dialogue box
•	After the user is satisfied with the responses and finalizes on a model which he thinks as appropriate for his task. He can choose the deploy the chatbot so that it can be used for future uses as well.
•	Data Entry:
-	Choose a model which gave the appropriate response for your prompts.
-	Choose the roles you want to give access of the chatbot. (Multiple roles can be selected).
-	Default pipeline and prompts will be selected (which were used during the creation of the chatbot). If the user wants, he can change Pipeline and Prompt as well during deployment.
o	API Calls:
-	Roles: This API responds with the available roles.
-	Pipelines: This API calls the available pipelines.
-	Prompts: This API gets the available prompts in the pipeline.

	Click on “Confirm Deployment” button

22.	Chatbot successfully deployed dialogue box
•	This confirmation message is generated when the chatbot has been successfully deployed and saved in the deployed application.
•	API Calls:
-	Deploy: This API posts the chatbot information in the database.
	 Click on “Done” button
23.	Deployed Application Page

•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/deployed-application
•	This page shows all the Deployed Applications that the user has deployed from the Experiment and Deploy option. The user can click on any of the application from the list to give prompts to.
•	API calls:
-	Deployments: This API gets all the available deployed applications from the database.
	Click on any of the existing deployed applications:

24.	Chatbot response page
•	This page contains all the past chats and responses that has been generated by the chatbot.
•	API Calls:
-	models: Gets the model chosen during the deployment.
-	response: This API gets the responses according to the prompts.
-	history: This API gets the history of chats between the user and the chatbot.
