Regulatory Audit Compliance:

1.	Regulatory & Audit Compliance
•	URL: 
•	The Compliance page lets users view, create, and link compliance regulations to pipelines. he page shows a list of regulations and their metadata, provides a form to create a new regulation (validates required fields), and enables attaching a regulation to a pipeline. The users can also open any existing compliance and review and download it as csv or pdf.
•	API Call:
-	compliances: This API returns the list of compliance regulations and their metadata.
	Click on “Create new” button:

2.	Regulatory and Audit Agent Page
•	URL: 
•	The Regulatory & Audit Agent page lets users run automated agents to generate or map compliance policies and audit checks.
•	Data Entry:
-	Compliance check name: Choose a name for the compliance
-	Select compliance document pipeline: Choose an existing pipeline to source documents.
-	Select regulations Type: Category filter for regulation classification.
-	Inputs on controls to be extracted: free-text list or keywords that the agent should extract from documents.
•	API Call:
-	pipelines: This API gives response for the existing pipelines.

	Click on the “Proceed to list policies”

3.	Policy Scanner Page
•	URL: 
•	Runs automated policy scanning agents against a selected regulation or pipeline to extract candidate policies and suggested Snowflake target tables. Displays a table of Policy ID, description, auto generated target tables, suggested count and match score with per row edit and bulk select. Actions include regenerate policy SQL, edit/override mappings, save changes, and approve selected policies.
•	API Call:
-	create-compliance:  This API inserts a new regulation/compliance record into DIM_REGULATION.
-	policies-from-agent: This API forwards a user prompt to the Snowflake policy agent to extract candidate policies.
-	policies: Returns policies for a given regulationId.
-	approvePolicies: Accepts body validates and extracts policy IDs, deduplicates them, and updates DIM_POLICY to set APPROVAL_STATUS = 'APPROVED' for the given IDs.
	Click on “View Approved Policies”

4.	Approved Policies Page
•	Displays the list of approved policies for a selected compliance review.
•	API Call:
-	approved: This API returns the list of APPROVED policies for a supplied regulationId.
	Click on “Generate Snowflake Mapping”

5.	Snowflake Mapping Page
•	Review and validate auto generated Snowflake target mappings for extracted policies, showing Policy ID, description, suggested target tables and suggested counts.
•	API calls:
-	mapping: Returns the list of mapped policies and target table/column information for a given regulationId.
-	mapping_agent: Forwards a user prompt to the Snowflake mapping agent to generate mapping suggestions; returns the agent raw response and extracted text.
	Click on “Proceed to Mapped policies”
6.	List of Mapped Policies Page
•	Displays mapped policies with columns: Policy ID, Policy description, Semantic view, Target database/schema/table/column, match score/reason, mapping ID and approval status.
•	API Calls:
-	mapping: Returns the list of mapped policies and target table/column information for a given regulationId.
-	mapping_agent: Forwards a user prompt to the Snowflake mapping agent to generate mapping suggestions; returns the agent raw response and extracted text (When the user clicks on save).
	 Click on “Proceed to Compliance Check” button
7.	Compliance Check Results Page
•	Shows compliance check results for a selected review with a table of Policy ID, policy description and the generated SQL that found non compliant records. Users can download report in excel format by clicking on “GENERATE REPORT” button.
•	API Call:
-	generated_sql: This API returns stored/generated compliance check logic rows for inspection or export.
-	run-compliance: Triggers the compliance pipeline by calling Snowflake procedures then build excel file and downloads it.
	Click on “Proceed to Remediation Script” button

8.	Remediation Policy page
•	Shows generated remediation scripts for selected compliance findings (logicId/policyId) with columns for generated SQL, source result, comments, and approval status.
•	API Call:
-	remediation: Fetches remediation candidates from DIM_COMPLIANCE_CHECK_LOGIC_REGENERATE.
	Click on “Proceed to Remediation SQL”
9.	Remediation SQL Logic Page
•	Lists remediation logic entries (logicId, policyId, target table/column, generated SQL and source result) with approval status and timestamps.
•	API Call:
-	remediation: returns remediation candidates from DIM_COMPLIANCE_CHECK_LOGIC_REGENERATE.
	Click on “Schedule Job”
10.	Schedule Job dialogue box
•	Modal dialog to schedule a compliance/remediation job: choose frequency and start/end date range and hit Confirm to create the scheduled task.

	Click on “Confirm” button
11.	Confirm message for Job Schedule
•	Success modal confirming the compliance job was scheduled successfully.
•	API Call:
-	schedules: This API schedules a compliance job for a given regulationId by validating frequency and date range, inserting a JOB_SCHEDULES row and creating/resuming a Snowflake TASK.
-	compliances: This API returns the list of compliance regulations and their metadata.(After clicking on “Ok”).

	Click on the “Home” button

Lineage Graph:
 
1.	Lineage Graph Page
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/lineage-graph
•	A lineage graph describes how data flows and transforms across objects, showing which table, views and qury depends on which sources.
•	Data Entry:
-	Enter a graph name.
-	Choose a database.
-	Choose the schema as per requirement.
-	Choose the Object type (options: Both, Table and View).
-	Choose the Object name (shows options as per object type).
-	Choose direction of the lineage.
-	Choose if you want to inclue the columns or not in the graph.
-	Write the name of the column you want to include and distance.
•	API call:
-	database: This API gets the database from the backend.
-	schemas: This API gets the schemas from the database.
-	tables: This API gets the tables and it’s columns from the selected schema.
-	views: This API gets the views in the schema.

 
	Click on the “Generate” button:

2.	Graph created successfully
•	You can see all the generate graphs in the Generated graphs table below.
•	API call:
-	lineage: This API works on generating the lineage graph as per the requirements given.
	Click on the “view” icon in the Action column of Generated Graphs table
3.	Generated lineage graph page
•	This page shows the Lineage graph and also gives the option to export the graph in .xls format.
•	API call:
-	lineage: This API creates the lineage graph from the backend stored data.
-	current-user: This API fetches the current user.
-	current-role: This API fetches the current role of the user.
-	current-access: This API checks the access of the user.

	Click on “Services” in the menu panel.
4.	Registered Services Page

•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/services
•	This page shows the registred services available and also the contents of all services. Eg: “Name”, “Object type”, “Object Name”, “Description”, “Input Argument”, “Output Argument”.
•	API Call:
-	combined: This API gets all the services saved in the database.

	Click on “Register Sevice” to register a new service.
 
5.	Register New Service Page
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/services/register
•	Id the user want to register new service then he can do this through the register service page.
•	Data Entry:
-	Service Name: Write the name of the service.
-	Snowflake Object Type: Select the Object type.
-	Write the name of the object.
-	Write a discription for the service.
-	Put an input argument from within the Stored Procedure.
-	Give a Outputm argument.
-	Upload the SQL File you want to use for the service.
	Click on “Upload File” button
6.	Success message after uploading the file
•	URL: https://jgdedud-pihjdmo-capgemini-apac-poc.snowflakecomputing.app/services/register
•	This screen shows the SQL was file uploaded successfully.
