Folder Structure
Overview
This project is a full‑stack application deployed on Snowflake Snowpark Container Services (SPCS). It contains three independent components—React Frontend, Node.js Backend, and Nginx Router—which are deployed together inside a single Snowflake service because cross‑service networking is restricted and OAuth identity forwarding only works reliably when all containers run inside the same service.
Project Structure
The repository contains three main folders: react/, node/, and router/. Each component has its own Dockerfile, and all are built into separate container images. These images are deployed together in a single Snowflake service.
📂 node
📂 node/config/
Contains configuration files such as:
•	Database connection configuration
•	Environment based settings
•	Constants used across backend
📂 node/controllers/
Holds controller logic for each API endpoint.
Example responsibilities:
•	Processing requests
•	Running business logic
•	Returning responses to the frontend
📂 node/routes/
Defines all backend API routes.
Follows environment based prefix strategy:
•	/api/... in local development
•	/... in deployment
📂 node/docs/
Backend-specific documentation (API specs, design notes, etc.).
📂 node/node_modules/
Auto generated by npm. Contains all backend dependencies.
📄 .env (inside node/)
Environment variables for backend
(e.g., DB credentials, ports, Snowflake configs).
📄 server.js
Main entry point of backend.
Responsible for:
•	Loading env config
•	Setting API prefix (local vs deployment)
•	Registering routes
•	Starting Express server
📄 package.json / package-lock.json
Backend dependencies, scripts, and metadata.
📄 snowflake.log
Logs related to Snowflake integration (if enabled).
 
________________________________________
📂  react
react/ – Frontend (React + Vite)
Handles UI rendering, API consumption, RBAC display logic, and user interactions.
📂 react/src/
Core application source code:
•	Components
•	Pages
•	Hooks
•	Services (API calls)
•	State management
📂 react/public/
Static files served as-is (logos, manifest, icons).
📂 react/dist/
Production build output generated by vite build.
📂 react/docs/
Frontend documentation (UI flows, wireframes).
📂 react/node_modules/
Auto-generated frontend dependencies.
📄 .env
Frontend environment variables (e.g., API base URL).
📄 index.html
Root HTML template loaded by Vite.
📄 vite.config.ts
Vite configuration (dev server, proxies, build options).
📄 tsconfig.*.json
TypeScript configuration files for compiler rules.
📄 .prettierrc / .eslintrc.js
Code formatting and linting rules for frontend.
 
________________________________________
📂 router
router/ – Deployment Router (Nginx Configuration)
Used only during deployment (Snowflake SPCS reverse proxy setup).
 

Router (Nginx) Configuration
The Nginx router serves the React UI and forwards backend API requests. In deployment, it removes the `/api` prefix before forwarding requests to the backend because the backend does not internally use the `/api` prefix.

Router Configuration
events {
  worker_connections 1024;
}
http {
    server {
        listen 8080;
        listen [::]:8080;
        server_name localhost;
        location / { proxy_pass http://$FRONTEND_URL/; }
        location /api { rewrite /api/(.*) /$1 break; proxy_pass http://$BACKEND_URL/; }
    }
}

Frontend API Calls
The frontend must always call backend API endpoints using the `/api` prefix. Example: `/api/getData`. This is required so that the router can correctly forward traffic to the backend.

 Important Note: Local vs Deployment API Prefix Behaviour
To ensure smooth development and deployment of the React + Node.js application, a consistent API access pattern is required:
•	Frontend (React) should always call APIs using the /api/... prefix
•	Backend (Node.js) should: 
o	Accept /api/... routes locally
o	Accept non prefixed routes (e.g., /data) in deployment
This difference is necessary because Nginx strips the /api prefix when deployed.
Therefore, the backend must dynamically adjust its route prefix based on the environment.

Required Behaviour

Local Development
Component	API Path Used
Frontend	/api/data
Backend	/api/data
React and Node run separately → direct access to /api/...

Deployed Application:
Deployment
Component	API Path Used	Notes
Frontend	/api/data	No change required
Nginx Router	rewrites /api/data → /data	Removes /api prefix
Backend	/data	Must NOT include /api

Backend Snowflake Connection Logic
The backend automatically switches between two authentication modes: OAuth token (inside SPCS) and username/password (local environment).
 

Dockerization Strategy
Three Docker images—react, node, router—are built independently and then pushed to Snowflake using Snow CLI. The images are hosted inside Snowflake's Image Repository.
React
 
Node
 
Router
 

Deployment Workflow
Deployment steps:
1. Upload code to S3
2. Sync S3 → EC2
3. Build Docker images
4. Authenticate using Snow CLI
5. Push images to Snowflake
6. Create a single Snowflake service with all 3 containers
7. Get the public endpoint link

Single Service Architecture
All three components must run inside a single service because:
- Snowflake restricts cross‑service communication
- Internal routing would fail across separate services
- OAuth identity forwarding works only within a unified service
Thus, single service deployment is mandatory for stable communication.
 
And get the endpoints for the deployed app
      show endpoints in  service raise_app;
 

 System Workflow After Deployment
User → Router → React → /api → Router → Backend → Snowflake → Backend → React. The backend executes SQL using the user's Snowflake identity.
